the welcoming cheers that greet
the heir to the imperial throne

25
00:03:12,120 --> 00:03:14,248
proof positive
that India remains

26
00:03:14,360 --> 00:03:17,045
just as steadfastly loyal
to the Crown

27
00:03:17,160 --> 00:03:20,084
as it was in the days
of his great-grandmother

28
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:22,771
Queen Victoria.

29
00:03:24,200 --> 00:03:27,204
[light sitar music]

30
00:03:27,320 --> 00:03:35,683
<i>[music]</i>

31
00:03:49,880 --> 00:03:50,961
Wait there a minute.

32
00:03:51,080 --> 00:03:52,764
Sir.

33
00:03:55,800 --> 00:03:59,088
Which is the lady
that I must seize upon?

34
00:03:59,200 --> 00:04:02,522
This same is she,
and I do give you her.

35
00:04:02,680 --> 00:04:04,967
Why, then she's mine.

36
00:04:05,080 --> 00:04:06,286
Sweet, let me see your face.

37
00:04:06,400 --> 00:04:09,449
I am your husband,
if you like of me.

38
00:04:09,600 --> 00:04:13,286
Give me your hand
before this holy friar.

39
00:04:13,400 --> 00:04:15,448
Soft and fair, friar.

40
00:04:15,600 --> 00:04:17,045
Which is Beatrice?

41
00:04:17,160 --> 00:04:19,811
I answer to that name.

42
00:04:19,960 --> 00:04:21,610
What is your will?

43
00:04:21,720 --> 00:04:22,846
Do not you love me?

44
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:26,402
Why, no,
no more than reason.

45
00:04:26,560 --> 00:04:28,403
Do not you love me?

46
00:04:28,560 --> 00:04:30,881
Troth, no,
no more than reason.

47
00:04:31,040 --> 00:04:34,761
Why, then my cousin, Margaret,
and Ursula are much deceived,

48
00:04:34,880 --> 00:04:37,201
for they did swear you did.

49
00:04:44,760 --> 00:04:47,411
[applause]

50
00:04:55,360 --> 00:04:59,001
Oh, what a totally ghastly
audience.

51
00:04:59,120 --> 00:05:00,121
[laughs]

52
00:05:00,240 --> 00:05:02,049
I didn't think
they were too bad.

53
00:05:03,640 --> 00:05:09,170
And now for another
transformation scene.

54
00:05:12,600 --> 00:05:14,921
How to make myself
look respectable

55
00:05:15,040 --> 00:05:16,121
for Government House.

56
00:05:16,240 --> 00:05:17,844
Oh, I'm so excited!

57
00:05:17,960 --> 00:05:19,883
Me too.

58
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:21,650
Is Mr. Blunt waiting?

59
00:05:21,800 --> 00:05:23,848
He better be.

60
00:05:23,960 --> 00:05:26,361
You're quite serious
about him, aren't you?

61
00:05:26,520 --> 00:05:28,648
I know you don't approve.

62
00:05:28,760 --> 00:05:30,728
Oh, it's not my place
to approve.

63
00:05:30,840 --> 00:05:32,808
Oh, don't be
so mamby-pamby, Mabelle.

64
00:05:32,960 --> 00:05:35,611
You think he's not good enough
for me.

65
00:05:35,720 --> 00:05:37,324
I just don't understand you.

66
00:05:37,440 --> 00:05:39,124
I mean, you're so ambitious,

67
00:05:39,240 --> 00:05:41,402
and with your background,
you could-

68
00:05:41,560 --> 00:05:42,925
[knocking at door]

69
00:05:43,040 --> 00:05:43,962
Who is it?

70
00:05:44,120 --> 00:05:47,010
Come in.

71
00:05:47,160 --> 00:05:49,811
Well, come on, girls.

72
00:05:49,920 --> 00:05:51,160
The prince is waiting.

73
00:05:55,720 --> 00:05:58,883
The young prince
immerses himself wholeheartedly

74
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:01,844
in the exhausting schedule
of duties entailed

75
00:06:01,960 --> 00:06:04,884
in such a great enterprise.

76
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:07,287
In the stifling heat
of an Indian midsummer,

77
00:06:07,440 --> 00:06:08,930
the grandest reception of all

78
00:06:09,040 --> 00:06:14,126
is held at Government House,
Calcutta.

79
00:06:22,160 --> 00:06:24,208
There she is.

80
00:06:24,320 --> 00:06:26,926
Why aren't you dancing, Mabelle?

81
00:06:27,040 --> 00:06:29,327
Oh, it's so hot in there.

82
00:06:29,440 --> 00:06:32,171
Did you meet the Prince
of Wales, Mr. Blunt?

83
00:06:32,280 --> 00:06:35,921
No, never got closer
than five yards.

84
00:06:36,040 --> 00:06:37,644
We've got something
to tell you.

85
00:06:37,760 --> 00:06:39,728
Oh, no, Gerda, please.
You promised-

86
00:06:39,840 --> 00:06:42,525
- Alistair wants it kept secret
from his stuffy family,

87
00:06:42,640 --> 00:06:44,768
but we're going to be married!

88
00:06:44,880 --> 00:06:46,120
Oh.

89
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:49,289
Oh, that's wonderful.

90
00:06:51,360 --> 00:06:53,761
Congratulations, Mr. Blunt.

91
00:06:53,880 --> 00:06:54,847
When will this be?

92
00:06:54,960 --> 00:06:56,325
Quite soon, actually.

93
00:06:56,440 --> 00:06:59,922
Alistair's bank want him
back in London next month.

94
00:07:00,040 --> 00:07:01,644
Oh, come on, Alistair.

95
00:07:01,760 --> 00:07:04,047
I want to dance!

96
00:07:04,160 --> 00:07:06,367
Excuse us, please,
Miss Sainsbury Seale.

97
00:07:06,520 --> 00:07:09,569
[both laughing]

98
00:07:11,120 --> 00:07:15,205
And so at last,
time to say good-bye.

99
00:07:15,320 --> 00:07:19,803
As he leaves India, the jewel
of Britain's vast empire,

100
00:07:19,920 --> 00:07:21,649
the prince can look back
with pride

101
00:07:21,760 --> 00:07:24,366
at a job well done.

102
00:07:24,520 --> 00:07:26,124
We'd like to join
with the people of India

103
00:07:26,240 --> 00:07:30,962
in saying thank you and
God bless the Prince of Wales.

104
00:07:31,080 --> 00:07:34,243
[people cheering]

105
